class Metadata():
    def __init__(self):
        self.initialised = False # were all other values set already?
        
        # Camera coeficients
        self.mtx = None
        self.dist = None
        self.ploty = None
        self.xSize = None
        self.ySize = None

        # Color space thresholds 
        self.binary = ColorSpace()
        self.binary.rgb.chnl0 = (210, 255)
        self.binary.lab.chnl2 = (200, 255)
        self.binary.hls.chnl2 = (90, 255)

        # Sobel space thresholds
        self.sobel = Sobel()
        self.sobel.kernel = 3
        self.sobel.abs = (20, 100)
        self.sobel.mag = (50, 170)
        self.sobel.dir = (np.pi/2 * (4/10), np.pi/2 * (6/10))

        # Warping parameters
        # bigger x value makes trapezoid's upper side broader
        # bigger y value makes trapezoid's height smaller (could be adjusted with car speed)
        self.xyWrp = (2, 3.5)
        
        # Frame tracking
        self.frameHistory = []
        self.maxFrameHistory = 15
        self.maxPolCoefDelta = [1, 0.15, 0.1] # 100%, 15%, 10% change allowed

        # Lane tracking
        self.lLine = Line()
        self.rLine = Line()
        self.avgLaneCurve = 0
        self.laneCurveHist = []
        self.laneFitFailed = 3   # force calculation on first frame
        self.laneFitMaxFails = 3 # max consecutive frames we can use same fit if lane detect fails

    def reset(self):
        self.laneFitFailed = self.laneFitMaxFails
        #self.frameHistory = []
        self.laneCurveHist = []
        self.lLine.history_fit = []
        self.rLine.history_fit = []
        self.lLine.average_fit = None
        self.rLine.average_fit = None
        self.lLine.detected = False
        self.rLine.detected = False
        
    def getCameraMatrix(self, images, nx, ny):
        objpoints = []
        imgpoints = []

        objp = np.zeros((ny*nx, 3), np.float32)
        objp[:,:2] = np.mgrid[0:nx, 0:ny].T.reshape(-1,2)

        for fname in images:
            img = cv2.imread(fname)

            # Convert to grayscale
            gray = cv2.cvtColor(img, cv2.COLOR_RGB2GRAY)

            # Find the chessboard corners
            ret, corners = cv2.findChessboardCorners(gray, (nx, ny), None)

            if ret == True:
                objpoints.append(objp)
                imgpoints.append(corners)
                self.xSize = gray.shape[1]
                self.ySize = gray.shape[0]
                self.ploty = np.linspace(0, gray.shape[0]-1, gray.shape[0])
                self.avgFrames = np.zeros_like(gray)

        ret, mtx, dist, rvecs, tvecs = cv2.calibrateCamera(objpoints, imgpoints, gray.shape[::-1], None, None)

        self.mtx = mtx
        self.dist = dist
        self.initialised = True

    def pushHistory(self, array, newItem):
        # Get the index for the new insertion
        # 0 if just adding, 1 if moving window history 1 item
        indx = max(0, len(array) - self.maxFrameHistory + 1)
        # Move the sliding window array, oldest out, new one in
        return array[indx:] + [newItem]
     
# Define a class to receive the characteristics of each line detection
class Line():
    def __init__(self):
        # was the line detected in the last iteration?
        self.detected = False
        # x values of the last n fits of the line
        self.recent_xfitted = []
        #average x values of the fitted line over the last n iterations
        self.bestx = None
        #average of self.history_fit
        self.average_fit = None
        #polynomial coefficients averaged over the last n iterations
        self.history_fit = []
        #polynomial coefficients for the most recent fit
        self.current_fit = []
        #radius of curvature of the line in some units
        self.radius_of_curvature = None
        #distance in meters of vehicle center from the line
        self.line_base_pos = None
        #difference in fit coefficients between last and new fits
        self.diffs = np.array([0,0,0], dtype='float')
        #x values for detected line pixels
        self.allx = None
        #y values for detected line pixels
        self.ally = None

def process_frame(image_original):
    image_undist = cv2.undistort(image_original, system.mtx, system.dist, None, system.mtx)
    image_binary = fGetBinary(system, image_undist)
    image_warped = fWarp(system, image_binary)
    
    # fGetBinary() is ANDing results and I'm keeping history
    # of the detected lines. ANDing results reduces the noise
    # from "temporal" detections, then keeping track of what 
    # I detected and adding it to the new measure should give 
    # me a solid line on both sides. At first it will have a
    # fairly big uncertainty, eventually it should add up to 
    # a solid image, depending on the value of maxFrameHistory
    image_average = np.zeros_like(image_warped)
    system.frameHistory = system.pushHistory(system.frameHistory, image_warped)
    for i in range(0, len(system.frameHistory)):
        image_average[(system.frameHistory[i] == 1) | (image_average == 1)] = 1
    
    #if not system.lLine.detected or not system.rLine.detected:
    if system.laneFitFailed >= system.laneFitMaxFails:
        system.reset() # detection failed too many times in a row, clear history variables
        laneLines = fFindLanePixels(system, image_average)
    else:
        laneLines = fFindLanePixelsDiff(system, image_average)
    
    #if system.lLine.detected and system.rLine.detected:
    avgCurveRad, laneDev = fGetLaneStats(system, image_average, laneLines)

    image_annotated = fDrawLaneStats(system, image_undist, avgCurveRad, laneDev)
    image_annotated = fDrawLaneOverlay(system, image_annotated, image_binary)
    image_annotated = fDrawWarpOverlay(system, image_annotated, image_average)

    return image_annotated

# Funtion to warp a portion of an image
# system.xyWrp[0] => changes the region of interest delta in the X-axis
# system.xyWrp[1] => changes the region of interest delta in the Y-axis
# This method would be a lot more versatile if I could pass a
# measure of speed as a parameter to increase or reduce the
# area of interest. This would probably improve the quality
# of the lane detection on the 'harder_challenge_video'
def fWarp(system, image, offset = 30):
    
    z = 20 # split each axis in 'n' pieces
    littleUnderHalfZx = ((z/2) - system.xyWrp[0])/z
    littleOverHalfZx  = ((z/2) + system.xyWrp[0])/z
    littleOverHalfZy  = ((z/2) + system.xyWrp[1])/z
    lotUnderHalfZ     = 0 # 1/z
    lotOverHalfZ      = 1 # (z-1)/z

    src = np.float32([
        # a b
        # c d
        [system.xSize * littleUnderHalfZx, system.ySize * littleOverHalfZy], # xy for a
        [system.xSize * littleOverHalfZx , system.ySize * littleOverHalfZy], # xy for b
        [system.xSize * lotUnderHalfZ    , system.ySize                   ], # xy for c
        [system.xSize * lotOverHalfZ     , system.ySize                   ]  # xy for d
    ])

    dst = np.float32([
        # a b
        # c d
        [offset               , offset      ], 
        [system.xSize - offset, offset      ], 
        [offset               , system.ySize], 
        [system.xSize - offset, system.ySize]
    ])

    # Compute and apply perpective transform
    system.M = cv2.getPerspectiveTransform(src, dst)
    system.Minv = cv2.getPerspectiveTransform(dst, src)
    
    # keep same size as input image
    warped = cv2.warpPerspective(image, system.M, (system.xSize, system.ySize), flags=cv2.INTER_NEAREST)

    return warped

# Get a combined binary image from Color and Sobel space binaries
def fGetBinary(system, image_rgb):
    image_bin = fGetBinaryFrame(system, image_rgb)
    image_sob = fGetSobelFrame(system, image_rgb)

    # Ideally I'd like to AND both outputs, but colorspace filtering gives me lines
    # and sobel filtering gives me line edges, so ANDing the outputs ends up producing
    # almost empty images. ORing them gives nice lines, but also doubles the noise
    #
    # Hunch...
    # ANDing outputs will work better with more tolerant colorspace and sobel filtering
    # ORing output will work better with more restricting colorspace and sobel filtering
    #
    image_final = np.zeros_like(image_bin)
    image_final[(image_sob == 1) & (image_bin == 1)] = 1
    #image_final[(image_sob == 1) | (image_bin == 1)] = 1
    
    return image_final

# Get a binary image from Color space
def fGetBinaryFrame(system, image_rgb):
    r = system.binary.rgb.chnl0
    b = system.binary.lab.chnl2
    s = system.binary.hls.chnl2
    
    RGB_channel_R = colorspace_threshold(image_rgb, None, 0, r)
    LAB_channel_B = colorspace_threshold(image_rgb, cv2.COLOR_RGB2Lab, 2, b)
    HLS_channel_S = colorspace_threshold(image_rgb, cv2.COLOR_RGB2HLS, 2, s)

    binaryFrame = np.zeros_like(RGB_channel_R)
    binaryFrame[
        (RGB_channel_R == 1) |
        (LAB_channel_B == 1) |
        (HLS_channel_S == 1)
    ] = 1

    return binaryFrame

def colorspace_threshold(img, x2yCvt, channel, thresh):
    if x2yCvt is not None: 
        colorConv = cv2.cvtColor(img, x2yCvt)
    else:
        colorConv = img
        
    colorChannel = colorConv[:,:,channel]
    colorChannel = colorChannel * (255/np.max(colorChannel)) # normalise
    
    binary = np.zeros_like(colorChannel)
    binary[(colorChannel > thresh[0]) & (colorChannel <= thresh[1])] = 1    
    binary_output = np.copy(binary)
    
    return binary_output # Return the binary image

# Function that applies Sobel x or y, then takes 
# an absolute value and applies a threshold.
def abs_sobel_threshold(img, orient, thresh):    
    # Apply the following steps to img
    # 1) Convert to grayscale
    gray = cv2.cvtColor(img, cv2.COLOR_RGB2GRAY)
    # 2) Take the derivative in x or y given orient = 'x' or 'y'
    if (orient == 'x'):
        sobel = cv2.Sobel(gray, cv2.CV_64F, 1, 0)
    else:
        sobel = cv2.Sobel(gray, cv2.CV_64F, 0, 1)
    # 3) Take the absolute value of the derivative or gradient
    abs_sobel = np.absolute(sobel)
    # 4) Scale to 8-bit (0 - 255) then convert to type = np.uint8
    scaled_sobel = np.uint8(255*abs_sobel/np.max(abs_sobel))
    # 5) Create a mask of 1's where the scaled gradient magnitude 
        # is > thresh_min and < thresh_max
    sbinary = np.zeros_like(scaled_sobel)
    sbinary[(scaled_sobel >= thresh[0]) & (scaled_sobel <= thresh[1])] = 1
    # 6) Return this mask as your binary_output image
    binary_output = np.copy(sbinary)
    
    return binary_output # Return the binary image

# Function that applies Sobel x and y, then computes 
# the magnitude of the gradient and applies a threshold
def mag_threshold(img, sobel_kernel, thresh):

    # Convert to grayscale
    gray = cv2.cvtColor(img, cv2.COLOR_RGB2GRAY)
    # Take both Sobel x and y gradients
    sobelx = cv2.Sobel(gray, cv2.CV_64F, 1, 0, ksize=sobel_kernel)
    sobely = cv2.Sobel(gray, cv2.CV_64F, 0, 1, ksize=sobel_kernel)
    # Calculate the gradient magnitude
    gradmag = np.sqrt(sobelx**2 + sobely**2)
    # Rescale to 8 bit
    scale_factor = np.max(gradmag)/255 
    gradmag = (gradmag/scale_factor).astype(np.uint8) 
    # Create a binary image of ones where threshold is met, zeros otherwise
    binary_output = np.zeros_like(gradmag)
    binary_output[(gradmag >= thresh[0]) & (gradmag <= thresh[1])] = 1

    return binary_output # Return the binary image

# Function that applies Sobel x and y, then computes 
# the direction of the gradient and applies a threshold.
def dir_threshold(img, sobel_kernel, thresh):
    # Grayscale
    gray = cv2.cvtColor(img, cv2.COLOR_RGB2GRAY)
    # Calculate the x and y gradients
    sobelx = cv2.Sobel(gray, cv2.CV_64F, 1, 0, ksize=sobel_kernel)
    sobely = cv2.Sobel(gray, cv2.CV_64F, 0, 1, ksize=sobel_kernel)
    # Take the absolute value of the gradient direction, 
    # apply a threshold, and create a binary image result
    absgraddir = np.arctan2(np.absolute(sobely), np.absolute(sobelx))
    binary_output =  np.zeros_like(absgraddir)
    binary_output[(absgraddir >= thresh[0]) & (absgraddir <= thresh[1])] = 1

    return binary_output # Return the binary image

# Get a binary image from Sobel space
def fGetSobelFrame(system, image_rgb):
    x_binary = abs_sobel_threshold(image_rgb, 'x', system.sobel.abs)
    y_binary = abs_sobel_threshold(image_rgb, 'y', system.sobel.abs)
    mag_binary = mag_threshold(image_rgb, system.sobel.kernel, system.sobel.mag)
    dir_binary = dir_threshold(image_rgb, system.sobel.kernel, system.sobel.dir)
    sobelFrame = np.zeros_like(dir_binary)
    sobelFrame[((x_binary == 1) & (y_binary == 1)) | ((mag_binary == 1) & (dir_binary == 1))] = 1
    
    return sobelFrame

def fFitPolynomial(lPoly, rPoly):        
    lFit = np.polyfit(lPoly[1], lPoly[0], 2)
    rFit = np.polyfit(rPoly[1], rPoly[0], 2)
    return (lFit, rFit)

# Find lane pixels in a binarised and perspective transformed image
def fFindLanePixels(system, binary_warped, nwindows=15, margin=100, minpix=80):
    # Take a histogram of the bottom half of the image
    histogram = np.sum(binary_warped[binary_warped.shape[0]//2:,:], axis=0)

    # Find the peak of the left and right halves of the histogram
    # These will be the starting point for the left and right lines
    midpoint = np.int(histogram.shape[0]//2)
    leftx_base = np.argmax(histogram[:midpoint])
    rightx_base = np.argmax(histogram[midpoint:]) + midpoint

    # Set height of windows - based on nwindows above and image shape
    window_height = np.int(binary_warped.shape[0]//nwindows)
    
    # Identify the x and y positions of all nonzero pixels in the image
    nonzero = binary_warped.nonzero()
    nonzeroy = np.array(nonzero[0])
    nonzerox = np.array(nonzero[1])
    
    # Current positions to be updated later for each window in nwindows
    leftx_current = leftx_base
    rightx_current = rightx_base

    pleftx_current = leftx_current
    prightx_current = rightx_current
    
    # Create empty lists to receive left and right lane pixel indices
    left_lane_inds = []
    right_lane_inds = []

    # Step through the windows one by one
    for window in range(nwindows):
        # Identify window boundaries in x and y (and right and left)
        win_y_low = binary_warped.shape[0] - (window+1)*window_height
        win_y_high = binary_warped.shape[0] - window*window_height
        win_xleft_low = leftx_current - margin
        win_xleft_high = leftx_current + margin
        win_xright_low = rightx_current - margin
        win_xright_high = rightx_current + margin
        
        # Identify the nonzero pixels in x and y within the window #
        good_left_inds = (
                (nonzeroy >= win_y_low) & 
                (nonzeroy < win_y_high) & 
                (nonzerox >= win_xleft_low) & 
                (nonzerox < win_xleft_high)
            ).nonzero()[0]
        
        good_right_inds = (
                (nonzeroy >= win_y_low) & 
                (nonzeroy < win_y_high) & 
                (nonzerox >= win_xright_low) & 
                (nonzerox < win_xright_high)
            ).nonzero()[0]
        
        # Append these indices to the lists
        left_lane_inds.append(good_left_inds)
        right_lane_inds.append(good_right_inds)
        
        # If you found > minpix pixels, recenter next window on their mean position
        if len(good_left_inds) > minpix:
            leftx_current = np.int(np.mean(nonzerox[good_left_inds]))
            pleftx_current = leftx_current
        # else, take then tendency and slowly fade it out
        else:
            leftx_current = np.int(0.9*pleftx_current)
            
        if len(good_right_inds) > minpix:        
            rightx_current = np.int(np.mean(nonzerox[good_right_inds]))
            prightx_current = rightx_current
        else:
            rightx_current = np.int(0.9*prightx_current)

    # Concatenate the arrays of indices (previously was a list of lists of pixels)
    left_lane_inds = np.concatenate(left_lane_inds)
    right_lane_inds = np.concatenate(right_lane_inds)

    # Extract left and right line pixel positions
    leftxy = (nonzerox[left_lane_inds], nonzeroy[left_lane_inds])
    rightxy = (nonzerox[right_lane_inds], nonzeroy[right_lane_inds])

    system.lLine.detected = len(leftxy[0]) != 0 and len(leftxy[1]) != 0
    system.rLine.detected = len(rightxy[0]) != 0 and len(rightxy[1]) != 0

    if system.lLine.detected and system.rLine.detected:
        (lPoly, rPoly) = fFitPolynomial(leftxy, rightxy)
        (lValid, rValid) = fStackLastFit(system, lPoly, rPoly)
        if not lValid or not rValid:
            system.laneFitFailed = system.laneFitMaxFails # not making diff detection here, full fail!
            #print('Lane validation failed (', system.laneFitFailed, '/', system.laneFitMaxFails, ')')
        else:
            system.laneFitFailed = 0
    else:
        system.laneFitFailed = system.laneFitMaxFails # not making diff detection here, full fail!
        #print('Lane detection failed (', system.laneFitFailed, '/', system.laneFitMaxFails, ')')

    return (left_lane_inds, right_lane_inds)

# Provided a previous fit, try to calculate a new polynomial fit
def fFindLanePixelsDiff(system, binary_warped, margin=100):
    # Grab activated pixels
    nonzero = binary_warped.nonzero()
    nonzeroy = np.array(nonzero[0])
    nonzerox = np.array(nonzero[1])
    
    pleft_fit = system.lLine.average_fit
    pright_fit = system.rLine.average_fit
    
    # Set the area of search based on activated x-values
    # within the +/- margin of our polynomial function
    left_lane_inds = ((
        (pleft_fit[0]*(nonzeroy**2) + pleft_fit[1]*nonzeroy + pleft_fit[2] - margin)
            < nonzerox) & (nonzerox < 
        (pleft_fit[0]*(nonzeroy**2) + pleft_fit[1]*nonzeroy + pleft_fit[2] + margin)
    ))
    
    right_lane_inds = ((
        (pright_fit[0]*(nonzeroy**2) + pright_fit[1]*nonzeroy + pright_fit[2] - margin)
            < nonzerox) & (nonzerox < 
        (pright_fit[0]*(nonzeroy**2) + pright_fit[1]*nonzeroy + pright_fit[2] + margin)
    ))
    
    leftxy = (nonzerox[left_lane_inds], nonzeroy[left_lane_inds])
    rightxy = (nonzerox[right_lane_inds], nonzeroy[right_lane_inds])

    system.lLine.detected = leftxy is not None and len(leftxy[0]) != 0 and len(leftxy[1]) != 0
    system.rLine.detected = rightxy is not None and len(rightxy[0]) != 0 and len(rightxy[1]) != 0

    # If we found new fits, update them. Otherwise leave them unchanged
    # but keep track of our fail-count to  eventually force a full recalculation
    if system.lLine.detected and system.rLine.detected:
        (lPoly, rPoly) = fFitPolynomial(leftxy, rightxy)
        (lValid, rValid) = fStackLastFit(system, lPoly, rPoly)
        if not lValid or not rValid:
            system.laneFitFailed += 1 
            #print('Diff Lane validation failed (', system.laneFitFailed, '/', system.laneFitMaxFails, ')')
        else:
            system.laneFitFailed = 0
    else: 
        system.laneFitFailed += 1
        #print('Diff Lane detection failed (', system.laneFitFailed, '/', system.laneFitMaxFails, ')')
        
    return (left_lane_inds, right_lane_inds)

def fStackLastFit(system, lPoly, rPoly):
    # Take whatever comes if we didnt't have anything so far
    if system.lLine.average_fit is None:
        system.lLine.average_fit = lPoly

    if system.rLine.average_fit is None:
        system.rLine.average_fit = rPoly

    # Stack the last polynomial fit with the previous history
    # check if the values changed within a reasonable range compared to average
    lDelta = abs((system.lLine.average_fit - lPoly) / system.lLine.average_fit)
    lValidDelta = \
        lDelta[0] < system.maxPolCoefDelta[0] and \
        lDelta[1] < system.maxPolCoefDelta[1] and \
        lDelta[2] < system.maxPolCoefDelta[2]
   
    #print('abs((avg - lPoly) / avg):     ', lDelta, ' (', lValidDelta, ')')
    
    if lValidDelta:
        # Add the new result and calculate the average polynomial array
        system.lLine.history_fit = system.pushHistory(system.lLine.history_fit, lPoly)
        system.lLine.average_fit = sum(system.lLine.history_fit) / len(system.lLine.history_fit)
        
    # Same for right line
    rDelta = abs((system.rLine.average_fit - rPoly) / system.rLine.average_fit)
    rValidDelta = \
        rDelta[0] < system.maxPolCoefDelta[0] and \
        rDelta[1] < system.maxPolCoefDelta[1] and \
        rDelta[2] < system.maxPolCoefDelta[2]

    #print('abs((avg - rPoly) / avg):     ', rDelta, ' (', rValidDelta, ')')

    if rValidDelta:
        # Add the new result and calculate the average polynomial array
        system.rLine.history_fit = system.pushHistory(system.rLine.history_fit, rPoly)
        system.rLine.average_fit = sum(system.rLine.history_fit) / len(system.rLine.history_fit)
            
    return (lValidDelta, rValidDelta)

def fGetLaneStats(system, image_binary, laneLines):
    # Define conversions in x and y from pixels space to meters
    xm_per_pix = 1.5 * 3.7 / system.xSize # assume 1.x lane widths in the region of interest
    ym_per_pix = 18 / system.ySize        # assume 18 meters in the region of interest

    carPosition = system.xSize / 2 # assume camera is in the center of the car
    laneCenter = system.xSize / 2  # assume car is driving in the center
    (lCurveRad, rCurveRad, laneDev) = (0, 0, 0)

    nonzero = image_binary.nonzero()
    nonzeroy = np.array(nonzero[0])
    nonzerox = np.array(nonzero[1])

    leftx = nonzerox[laneLines[0]]
    lefty = nonzeroy[laneLines[0]] 
    rightx = nonzerox[laneLines[1]]
    righty = nonzeroy[laneLines[1]]
    
    # Fit new polynomials to x,y in real world space
    if len(leftx) != 0 and len(rightx) != 0:
        lCPoly = np.polyfit(lefty*ym_per_pix, leftx*xm_per_pix, 2)
        rCPoly = np.polyfit(righty*ym_per_pix, rightx*xm_per_pix, 2)
        
        lCurveRad = ((1 + (2*lCPoly[0]*system.ySize*ym_per_pix + lCPoly[1])**2)**1.5) / np.absolute(2*lCPoly[0])
        rCurveRad = ((1 + (2*rCPoly[0]*system.ySize*ym_per_pix + rCPoly[1])**2)**1.5) / np.absolute(2*rCPoly[0])
    
    lPoly = system.lLine.average_fit
    rPoly = system.rLine.average_fit
    
    # Find deviance to lane center
    if lPoly is not None and rPoly is not None:
        lLaneAtCar = lPoly[0]*system.ySize**2 + lPoly[1]*system.ySize + lPoly[2]
        rLaneAtCar = rPoly[0]*system.ySize**2 + rPoly[1]*system.ySize + rPoly[2]
        laneCenter = (lLaneAtCar + rLaneAtCar) / 2
    
        avgCurveRad = (lCurveRad + rCurveRad) / 2
        laneDev = (carPosition - laneCenter) * xm_per_pix

        system.laneCurveHist = system.pushHistory(system.laneCurveHist, avgCurveRad)
        system.avgLaneCurve = sum(system.laneCurveHist) / len(system.laneCurveHist)
    
    return system.avgLaneCurve, laneDev

def fDrawLaneStats(system, image, avgCurveRad, laneDev):
    image_copy = np.copy(image)
    font = cv2.FONT_HERSHEY_DUPLEX
    text = 'Curve radius: ' + '{:04.2f}'.format(avgCurveRad) + 'm'
    if not system.lLine.detected or not system.rLine.detected:
        text = text + ' (*)'
    cv2.putText(image_copy, text, (40,70), font, 1, (0,255,155), 2, cv2.LINE_AA)
    direction = 'right'
    if laneDev < 0:
        direction = 'left'
    absLaneDev = abs(laneDev)
    text = 'Car deviates ' + '{:04.2f}'.format(absLaneDev) + 'm to the ' + direction
    cv2.putText(image_copy, text, (40,120), font, 1, (0,255,155), 2, cv2.LINE_AA)
    return image_copy

def fDrawLaneOverlay(system, image_color, image_binary):
    image_copy = np.copy(image_color)

    lPoly = system.lLine.average_fit
    rPoly = system.rLine.average_fit

    if lPoly is not None and rPoly is not None:
        lLaneAtCar = lPoly[0]*system.ploty**2 + lPoly[1]*system.ploty + lPoly[2]
        rLaneAtCar = rPoly[0]*system.ploty**2 + rPoly[1]*system.ploty + rPoly[2]

        # Create an image to draw the lines on
        warp_zero = np.zeros_like(image_binary).astype(np.uint8)
        color_warp = np.dstack((warp_zero, warp_zero, warp_zero))

        # Recast the x and y points into usable format for cv2.fillPoly()
        pts_left = np.array([np.transpose(np.vstack([lLaneAtCar, system.ploty]))])
        pts_right = np.array([np.flipud(np.transpose(np.vstack([rLaneAtCar, system.ploty])))])
        pts = np.hstack((pts_left, pts_right))

        # Draw the lane onto the warped blank image
        cv2.fillPoly(color_warp, np.int_([pts]), (0, 255, 0))

        # Warp the blank back to original image space using inverse perspective matrix (Minv)
        newwarp = cv2.warpPerspective(color_warp, system.Minv, (system.xSize, system.ySize))  
        return cv2.addWeighted(image_copy, 1, newwarp, 0.3, 0) # Combine the result with the original image
    else:
        return image_copy

def fDrawWarpOverlay(system, image_main, image_second):
    image_thumb = cv2.resize(image_second, (0,0), fx = 0.2, fy = 0.2)

    # show thumb at upper right corner
    cornerMargin = 20
    x = image_main.shape[1] - (image_thumb.shape[1] + cornerMargin)
    y = cornerMargin

    # Keep image size, expand to same color channel size
    thumb_w = image_thumb.shape[1]
    thumb_h = image_thumb.shape[0]
    thumb_chnls = image_main.shape[2]
    
    # Create new image and fill all channels with thumb data
    thumb_copy = np.zeros([thumb_h, thumb_w, thumb_chnls], np.uint8)
    for i in range(0, thumb_chnls):
        thumb_copy[:,:,i] = image_thumb

    image_copy = np.copy(image_main)
    image_copy = fPasteImage(image_main, thumb_copy, (x, y))    
    return image_copy

# from https://opencv-python-tutroals.readthedocs.io/
#  en/latest/py_tutorials/py_core/py_image_arithmetics/py_image_arithmetics.html#bitwise-operations
def fPasteImage(img1, img2, coords):
    # get the region of interest for the main image
    rows, cols, channels = img2.shape
    roi = img1[coords[1]:coords[1]+rows, coords[0]:coords[0]+cols]

    # Now create a mask and create its inverse mask also
    img2gray = cv2.cvtColor(img2,cv2.COLOR_BGR2GRAY)
    ret, mask = cv2.threshold(img2gray, 0, 255, cv2.THRESH_BINARY)
    mask_inv = cv2.bitwise_not(mask)

    # Now black-out the area for the thumb in ROI
    img1_bg = cv2.bitwise_and(roi, roi, mask = mask_inv)
    
    # Take only region of thumb from thumb image.
    img2_fg = cv2.bitwise_and(img2, img2, mask = mask)

    # Put thumb in ROI and modify the main image
    dst = cv2.add(img1_bg, img2_fg)
    img1[coords[1]:coords[1]+rows, coords[0]:coords[0]+cols] = dst
    
    return img1
